<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
To directly quote what someone says or has said, repeat their words exactly and follow with @HI{{to@KJ{{say}}u}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{lie*down}}ru maeni [o@KJ{{rest}}minasai]to@KJ{{say}}imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      We say "Good night" before we go to bed.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
To quote indirectly, use the plain form before @HI{{to@KJ{{say}}u}}. The tense of the quoted text is 
unaffected by the tense of the main sentence.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{mira-}}sanha @KJ{{come^week east^capital}}he @KJ{{exit^long}}suruto@KJ{{say}}imashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Miller said that he would go to Tokyo on a business trip next week.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
If it appears at the end of a sentence @HI{{to@KJ{{say}}u}} indicates hearsay ("I heard that ...", "It is said that ...").
This form is most often used in written Japanese.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@KJ{{environs}}riha@KJ{{once*upon*a*time}},@KJ{{wide}}i@KJ{{plains^meadow}}datta@EM{{toiu}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Long ago, this neighbourhood used to be fields, I heard.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

